To create a pulsing effect that gradually increases and decreases the size of multiple elements on a webpage, you can use CSS animation keyframes and apply them to a class that will target the specific elements.

Here's an example of how to create a pulsing effect on multiple elements:

HTML:

```html
<div class="pulse"></div>
<div class="pulse"></div>
<div class="pulse"></div>
```

CSS:

```css
.pulse {
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  background-color: blue;
  animation: pulse 2s infinite;
}

@keyframes pulse {
  0% {
    transform: scale(1);
  }
  50% {
    transform: scale(1.2);
  }
  100% {
    transform: scale(1);
  }
}
```

In this example, we create three elements with the class "pulse" and set their width, height, and background color. We then apply a CSS animation named "pulse" to each of these elements with a duration of 2 seconds and an infinite loop.

The keyframes of the "pulse" animation gradually increase and decrease the size of each element, using the transform property to adjust the scale of the elements. At the beginning of the animation (0%), the elements have a scale of 1. During the midpoint (50%), the elements increase to a scale of 1.2. At the end of the animation (100%), the elements return to their original scale of 1.

You can customize the speed and duration of the pulsing effect by adjusting the values in the "animation" property of the ".pulse" class. For example, changing the duration from 2s to 1s will make the pulsing effect twice as fast. Similarly, changing the "infinite" value to a specific number of repetitions will limit the number of times the pulsing effect occurs.

